    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-01T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-01T14:00:00-05:00" n="1012"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1012">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.01/100: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Scotten</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-01T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >June 1, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>546. The legal aspects of the new Government appear to be as follows: Velasco
                    Ibarra is in no sense a constitutional president although he has been put into
                    power by the will of the vast majority of the population. His announcement that
                    a Constituent Assembly will meet on August 10 means that delegates to this
                    Assembly will be elected between now and that date. The Assembly itself will
                    draw up a constitution for the Republic and will itself elect a President of the
                    Republic who will of course be Velasco Ibarra.</p>
                <p>Until the Assembly meets, Velasco Ibarra in a legal sense could be termed either
                    a dictator or a provisional president with no basis under the law for holding
                    power.</p>
                <p>Velasco Ibarra has announced that the 196 [<hi rend="italic">1906</hi>]
                    Constitution under which the Arroyo administration operated, will remain in
                    force until the Assembly meets except in so far as it contradicts the aims of
                    the revolution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Scotten</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
